  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international framework established\n- Basic reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Increased focus on drug-related money laundering\n- United Nations Convention against drug trafficking (1988)\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n\n3. 1990s Transformation\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- More comprehensive international standards\n- Expanded legal definitions of money laundering\n- Stricter reporting requirements\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced anti-terrorism financing measures\n- Increased information sharing\n- Broader regulatory oversight\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- More stringent Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Complex beneficial ownership transparency rules\n- Greater emphasis on technology-driven compliance\n\n6. Global Regulatory Progression\n- Continuous refinement of international standards\n- Increased cross-border collaboration\n- Periodic updates to legal frameworks\n- Adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n\nThese developments reflect growing complexity in financial systems and criminal strategies.",
